13 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
14 That Section(s) 21–259.3 of Article – Health – General of the Annotated Code of Maryland
15 be renumbered to be Section(s) 21–259.4.
16 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
17 as follows:
18 Article – Commercial Law
19 13–301.
20 Unfair, abusive, or deceptive trade practices include any:
21 (14) Violation of a provision of:
22 (xlvii) Title 14, Subtitle 50 of this article; [or]
23 (xlviii) Section 13–411.1(c)(2) of the Transportation Article; or
24 (XLIX) SECTION 21–259.2 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL
25 ARTICLE; OR
26 Article – Health – General
27 21–101.
28 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
29 (e) (1) “Cosmetic” means any substance, or any component of a substance, that
30 is intended to be rubbed, poured, sprinkled, or sprayed on, introduced into, or otherwise

4 SENATE BILL 656
1 applied to the human body for cleansing, beautifying, promoting attractiveness, or altering
2 appearance.
3 (2) “Cosmetic” does not include soap.
4 21–259.2.
5 (a) In this section:
6 (1) “Ingredient” means any single chemical entity or mixture used as a
7 component in the manufacture of a cosmetic product; and
8 (2) “Ingredient” does not include an incidental ingredient, as described in
9 21 C.F.R. § 701.3(l).
10 (b) Except as provided in subsection (c) of this section, a person may not
11 knowingly manufacture, sell, deliver, hold, or offer for sale in the State a cosmetic product
12 that contains any of the following intentionally added ingredients:
13 (1) Dibutyl phthalate (CAS no. 84–74–2);
14 (2) Diethylhexyl phthalate (CAS no. 117–81–7);
15 (3) Formaldehyde (CAS no. 50–00–0);
16 (4) Paraformaldehyde (CAS no. 30525–89–4);
17 (5) Methylene glycol (CAS no. 463–57–0);
18 (6) Quaternium–15 (CAS no. 51229–78–8);
19 (7) Mercury (CAS no. 7439–97–6);
20 (8) Isobutylparaben (CAS no. 4247–02–3);
21 (9) Isopropylparaben (CAS no. 4191–73–5);
22 (10) m–Phenylenediamine and its salts (CAS no. 108–45–2);
23 (11) o–Phenylenediamine and its salts (CAS no. 95–54–5); or
24 (12) The following per– and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) and their
25 salts:
26 (i) Perfluorooctane sulfonate (PFOS) or
27 heptadecafluorooctane–1–sulfonic acid (CAS no. 1763–23–1);

SENATE BILL 656 5
1 (ii) Potassium perfluorooctanesulfonate or potassium
2 heptadecafluorooctane–1–sulfonate (CAS no. 2795–39–3);
3 (iii) Diethanolamine perfluorooctane sulfonate (CAS no.
4 70225–14–8);
5 (iv) Ammonium perfluorooctane sulfonate or ammonium
6 heptadecafluorooctanesulfonate (CAS no. 29081–56–9);
7 (v) Lithium perfluorooctane sulfonate or lithium
8 heptadecafluorooctanesulfonate (CAS no. 29457–72–5);
9 (vi) Perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA) (CAS no. 335–67–1);
10 (vii) Ammonium pentadecafluorooctanoate (CAS no. 3825–26–1);
11 (viii) Nonadecafluorodecanoic acid (CAS no. 335–76–2);
12 (ix) Ammonium nonadecafluorodecanoate (CAS no. 3108–42–7);
13 (x) Sodium nonadecafluorodecanoate (CAS no. 3830–45–3);
14 (xi) Perfluorononanoic acid (PFNA) (CAS no. 375–95–1);
15 (xii) Sodium heptadecafluorononanoate (CAS no. 21049–39–8); or
16 (xiii) Ammonium perfluorononanoate (CAS no. 4149–60–4).
17 (c) A person is not in violation of this section if the person manufactures, sells,
18 delivers, holds, or offers for sale in the State a cosmetic product that:
19 (1) Was manufactured through a process intended to comply with this
20 section; and
21 (2) Contains a technically unavoidable trace quantity of an ingredient
22 listed in subsection (b) of this section due to:
23 (i) An impurity of a natural or synthetic ingredient;
24 (ii) The manufacturing process;
25 (iii) Storage; or
26 (iv) Packaging.

6 SENATE BILL 656
1 (D) (1) IN ADDITION TO ANY OTHER PENALTIES UNDER THIS TITLE, A
2 PERSON WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION IS LIABLE FOR CIVIL DAMAGES RESULTING
3 FROM ACTUAL HARM SUSTAINED BY THE INDIVIDUAL RESULTING FROM THE
4 VIOLATION.
5 (2) AN ACTION UNDER THIS SECTION MUST BE BROUGHT WITHIN 3
6 YEARS AFTER THE DATE ON WHICH THE PLAINTIFF DISCOVERED OR REASONABLY
7 SHOULD HAVE DISCOVERED THAT THE EXPOSURE TO AN INGREDIENT IN VIOLATION
8 OF THIS SECTION WAS THE PROXIMATE CAUSE OF THE INJURY SUSTAINED BY THE
9 PLAINTIFF.
10 (3) IN ANY ACTION BROUGHT TO ENFORCE THIS SECTION, A COURT
11 MAY AWARD REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES TO A PREVAILING PLAINTIFF:
12 (I) TREBLE DAMAGES;
13 (II) IF THE VIOLATION WAS WILLFUL, PUNITIVE DAMAGES; AND
14 (III) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES.
15 (E) (1) THE DEPARTMENT MAY INVESTIGATE ANY COMPLAINT ALLEGING
16 THAT A PERSON HAS VIOLATED THIS SECTION.
17 (2) ON RECEIPT OF A COMPLAINT, A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE
18 DEPARTMENT, AT A REASONABLE TIME, MAY ENTER AND INSPECT THE PREMISES OF
19 THE PERSON LOCATED IN THE STATE TO DETERMINE COMPLIANCE WITH THIS
20 SECTION.
21 (3) THE PERSON MAY NOT:
22 (I) REFUSE TO GRANT ACCESS TO A REPRESENTATIVE WHO
23 REQUESTS TO ENTER AND INSPECT THE PREMISES OF THE PERSON UNDER
24 PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION; OR
25 (II) INTERFERE WITH AN INSPECTION UNDER PARAGRAPH (2)
26 OF THIS SUBSECTION.
27 (4) AN INVESTIGATION OF A PREMISES OF A PERSON CONDUCTED
28 UNDER THIS SUBSECTION MAY INCLUDE SAMPLING OF A COSMETIC PRODUCT TO
29 DETERMINE IF THE COSMETIC PRODUCT CONTAINS A TECHNICALLY UNAVOIDABLE
30 TRACE QUANTITY OF AN INGREDIENT LISTED IN SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION.
31 21–259.3.

SENATE BILL 656 7
1 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “FUND” MEANS THE HARMFUL HAIR CHEMICAL
2 RESTITUTION FUND.
3 (B) THERE IS A HARMFUL HAIR CHEMICAL RESTITUTION FUND.
4 (C) THE PURPOSE OF THE FUND IS TO SUPPORT THE RESEARCH AND
5 TREATMENT, INCLUDING SCREENINGS AND DIAGNOSIS, OF FIBROIDS, UTERINE
6 CANCER, HAIR LOSS, AND RELATED CONDITIONS CAUSED BY HARMFUL HAIR
7 CHEMICALS.
8 (D) THE ATTORNEY GENERAL SHALL ADMINISTER THE FUND.
9 (E) (1) THE FUND IS A SPECIAL, NONLAPSING FUND THAT IS NOT
10 SUBJECT TO § 7–302 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE.
11 (2) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL HOLD THE FUND SEPARATELY,
12 AND THE COMPTROLLER SHALL ACCOUNT FOR THE FUND.
13 (F) THE FUND CONSISTS OF:
14 (1) ALL FUNDS, EXCLUDING FUNDS RECEIVED BY THE AGGRIEVED
15 PARTY AND THE COSTS OF THE ACTION THE ATTORNEY GENERAL IS ENTITLED TO
16 RECOVER, RECEIVED BY THE DIVISION OF CONSUMER PROTECTION IN THE OFFICE
17 OF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL FROM ENFORCING § 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE
18 UNDER THE CONSUMER PROTECTION ACT; AND
19 (2) INTEREST EARNINGS OF THE FUND.
20 (G) (1) THE FUND SHALL BE USED FOR:
21 (I) PROVIDING GRANTS FOR THE SUPPORT OF THE RESEARCH
22 AND TREATMENT, INCLUDING SCREENINGS AND DIAGNOSIS, OF FIBROIDS, UTERINE
23 CANCER, HAIR LOSS, AND RELATED CONDITIONS CAUSED BY HARMFUL HAIR
24 CHEMICALS;
25 (II) CARRYING OUT ANY LAWS ENACTED TO BENEFIT VICTIMS
26 OF A VIOLATION OF § 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE; AND
27 (III) PROVIDING RESTITUTION TO VICTIMS OF A VIOLATION OF §
28 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
29 (2) TO QUALIFY FOR A GRANT FROM THE FUND, AN APPLICANT FOR A
30 GRANT UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)(I) OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL BE REQUIRED TO:

8 SENATE BILL 656
1 (I) FILE A COMPLAINT WITH THE ATTORNEY GENERAL FOR A
2 VIOLATION OF § 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE; AND
3 (II) HAVE SUSTAINED HARM AS A RESULT OF A VIOLATION OF §
4 21–259.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
5 (H) (1) THE STATE TREASURER SHALL INVEST THE MONEY OF THE FUND
6 IN THE SAME MANNER AS OTHER STATE MONEY MAY BE INVESTED.
7 (2) ANY INTEREST EARNINGS OF THE FUND SHALL BE CREDITED TO
8 THE FUND.
9 (I) EXPENDITURES FROM THE FUND MAY BE MADE ONLY IN ACCORDANCE
10 WITH THE STATE BUDGET.
11 (J) MONEY EXPENDED FROM THE FUND FOR THE SUPPORT OF RESEARCH
12 AND TREATMENT UNDER SUBSECTION (G) OF THIS SECTION IS SUPPLEMENTAL TO
13 AND IS NOT INTENDED TO TAKE THE PLACE OF FUNDING THAT OTHERWISE WOULD
14 BE APPROPRIATED FOR THE SUPPORT OF RESEARCH AND TREATMENT.
15 Article – State Finance and Procurement
16 6–226.
17 (a) (2) (i) This paragraph does not apply in fiscal years 2024 through 2028.
18 (ii) Notwithstanding any other provision of law, and unless
19 inconsistent with a federal law, grant agreement, or other federal requirement or with the
20 terms of a gift or settlement agreement, net interest on all State money allocated by the
21 State Treasurer under this section to special funds or accounts, and otherwise entitled to
22 receive interest earnings, as accounted for by the Comptroller, shall accrue to the General
23 Fund of the State.
24 (iii) The provisions of subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph do not
25 apply to the following funds:
26 212. the Department of Social and Economic Mobility Special
27 Fund; [and]
28 213. the Population Health Improvement Fund; AND
29 214. THE HARMFUL HAIR CHEMICALS RESTITUTION
30 FUND.
31 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:

SENATE BILL 656 9
1 (a) (1) The Maryland Department of Health, in conjunction with the Office of
2 the Attorney General, shall develop a plan for the administration of a special fund to support
3 the research and treatment, including screenings and diagnosis, of fibroids, uterine cancer,
4 hair loss, and related conditions caused by harmful hair chemicals that consists of:
5 (i) all funds, excluding funds received by the aggrieved party and the
6 costs of the action the Attorney General is entitled to recover, received by the Division of
7 Consumer Protection in the Office of the Attorney General from enforcing § 21–259.2 of the
8 Health – General Article under the Consumer Protection Act; and
9 (ii) interest earnings of the fund.
10 (2) The plan developed under paragraph (1) of this subsection shall include
11 the best method of using the money in the fund to achieve the purpose of the special fund.
12 (b) On or before December 1, 2026, the Maryland Department of Health, in
13 conjunction with the Office of the Attorney General, shall report the plan developed under
14 subsection (a) of this section to the Senate Finance Committee and the House Health
15 Committee, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article.
16 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
17 July 1, 2026.
Approved:
